{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17415502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17415502"},"attributes":{"position":52,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T09:06:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T09:06:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15719"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536229"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:04:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:04:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15719"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"15719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15719"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.09,0.02,0.27,0.6]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8410"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115435"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8410"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15719"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97438"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1533"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"3190"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3915"},{"type":"tags","id":"5967"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20257"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30435"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45089"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45140"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48452"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115435"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with three days of progressive confusion and mild drowsiness. He has metastatic small cell lung cancer diagnosed two months ago and is currently receiving chemotherapy. He has no other significant medical history. His regular medications are ondansetron and paracetamol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears euvolaemic. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 128/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. He is confused and disoriented to time and place but responds appropriately to verbal commands. There are no focal neurological signs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium: 118 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium: 4.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum osmolality: 248 mOsm/kg (285-295)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine osmolality: 520 mOsm/kg (300-900)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine sodium: 65 mmol/L (40-220)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Demeclocycline","Normal saline infusion","Tolvaptan","Fluid restriction","3% hypertonic saline"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptomatic hyponatraemia due to Syndrome of Inappropriate Antidiuretic Hormone secretion (SIADH), which is a common paraneoplastic complication of small cell lung cancer. The diagnosis is supported by low serum sodium, low serum osmolality, inappropriately concentrated urine (high urine osmolality), and relatively high urine sodium in a euvolaemic patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E3% hypertonic saline\u003C/strong\u003E is a reasonable first step in management given the neurological features including confusion, disorientation, and drowsiness. It is also the mainstay when patients present with seizures, coma, or severe altered consciousness. Hypertonic saline allows for rapid improvement, but caution must be exerted to ensure rate of correction is controlled to avoid central pontine myelinolysis. In cases of chronic hyponatraemia or where duration of hypoatraenmia is not known, the rate of sodium correction should not exceed 8 mmol/L in 24 hours. Regular monitoring of serum sodium is essential during treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluid restriction\u003C/strong\u003E will be mainstay of management ongoing, but first, the patient needs symptomatic management through hypertonic saline. Fluid restriction to 800-1000 mL per day is typically effective for SIADH and allows gradual correction of sodium levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal saline\u003C/strong\u003E infusion would be inappropriate as it may worsen hyponatraemia in SIADH. The high urine sodium concentration means that the infused sodium would be excreted while free water is retained, potentially worsening the hyponatraemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDemeclocycline\u003C/strong\u003E can be used as a second-line treatment for chronic SIADH but takes several days to work and has significant side effects including nephrotoxicity. It is not appropriate as first-line therapy for acute symptomatic hyponatraemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETolvaptan\u003C/strong\u003E, a vasopressin receptor antagonist, is effective but requires specialist initiation and careful monitoring. While it could be considered if fluid restriction fails, it is not typically used as first-line therapy in the emergency setting.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypertonic saline is indicated for symptomatic SIADH with neurological symptoms including seizure, confusion or altered consciousness.","Small cell lung cancer commonly causes paraneoplastic SIADH.","The diagnosis of SIADH requires low serum sodium, low serum osmolality, inappropriately concentrated urine, and euvolaemia.","Fluid restriction is an effective management strategy longer-term for hyponatraemia due to SIADH."],"references":["Mentrasti G, Scortichini L, Torniai M, Giampieri R, Morgese F, Rinaldi S, Berardi R. Syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (SIADH): optimal management. Therapeutics and clinical risk management. 2020 Jul 24:663-72. Available online at ; https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/pdf/10.2147/TCRM.S206066","Annabelle M Warren, Mathis Grossmann, Mirjam Christ-Crain, Nicholas Russell, Syndrome of Inappropriate Antidiuresis: From Pathophysiology to Management, Endocrine Reviews, Volume 44, Issue 5, October 2023, Pages 819\u2013861, https://doi.org/10.1210/endrev/bnad010","Rondon-Berrios, Helbert, and Richard H. Sterns. \u201cHypertonic Saline for Hyponatremia: Meeting Goals and Avoiding Harm.\u201d American Journal of Kidney Diseases, vol. 79, no. 6, Sept. 2021, https://doi.org/10.1053/j.ajkd.2021.07.020."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97438"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15719"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97438"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T17:37:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T17:39:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8410"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115435"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":nul